Skyrim Campaign Guide - For Adventure Creation
Campaign Overview & Setting
The World: An Alternate Skyrim
This campaign takes place in a parallel universe where the Dragonborn exists but has abandoned their destiny. Instead of answering the call to save the world, they've chosen a simple life as a fisherman, ignoring the growing threats across Skyrim. This creates a power vacuum where other heroes—the player characters—must step up to handle the crises that would normally fall to the Dragonborn.
The Bjorn Connection: The party's primary mode of transport and recurring NPC contact is Old Bjorn. He is not just a driver, but a merchant who initially hires the party for protection while he transports his goods between holds. This establishes a working relationship built on mutual benefit. Later in the campaign, when High King Torygg charters the party as "The Skyrim Wardens," he will also formally hire Bjorn as their dedicated transport, recognizing the value of their pre-existing trust and Bjorn's reliability.
Campaign Structure: Anthology Adventures
Episodic Format: Each session or short arc is a complete, self-contained adventure with a clear beginning, middle, and end.
Flexible Continuity: Players will bring the same characters to each adventure, but the structure is robust enough to accommodate guest players or new characters if needed.
Escalating Backdrop: While each adventure stands alone, the overarching threats to Skyrim will grow more severe in the background.
Heroic Opportunity: The players are not the "chosen ones." They are adventurers who, through their actions, become the heroes Skyrim desperately needs.



The Core Design Philosophy: Three Pillars
Pillar 1: The Self-Contained Story (The Episode)
The "Tavern to Tomb" Model: Every adventure must function as a complete one-shot. It needs a clear hook, a journey or investigation, a central "dungeon" (be it a ruin, a political conspiracy, or a vampire's lair), and a satisfying resolution.
Clear, Actionable Goals: The players should always have a clear, immediate objective.
Guaranteed Reward: At the end of every successful adventure, the party receives the promised tangible rewards (gold, items) and 1 Advancement Point.
Pillar 2: The Living World (The Overarching Plot)
The Consequence Calendar: The world does not wait. Between sessions, unaddressed threats will evolve. We will track 3-5 ongoing threats across Skyrim. After each adventure, we will advance one or two of these threats to their next stage of severity.
The Rumor Mill: The main plot will not be a quest marker. It will be revealed organically through rumors, NPC conversations, and the changing state of the world, making the players feel like they are discovering the main plot, not just being led by it.
Pillar 3: Character-Driven Narrative (The Personal Arcs)
The "Order of Business" Phase: The beginning of each new "arc" (when the party arrives in a new city) is dedicated to the characters' personal stories. This is a structured "downtime" that is played out in scenes, allowing every player a moment in the spotlight to pursue personal goals, interact with key NPCs, or deal with backstory consequences.
Reputation Matters (Overhauled for a Long-Form Campaign): The party is not anonymous. Their deeds have consequences. We will track their reputation on a five-tier scale that reflects a full, 20-25 AP campaign.
Tier 1: The Unknown (0 AP)
Title: Sellswords, Mercenaries.
In-World Effect: The party is just another group of armed travelers. They are unknown and must prove their worth to get their first jobs. NPCs are wary and guards are suspicious.


Tier 2: The Noteworthy (1-4 AP)
Title: Capable Adventurers, "The Ones Who Handled That Business in..."
In-World Effect: Their name is known in the hold where they achieved their first successes. Stewards and minor quest-givers might have heard of them, making it easier to find work. They've proven they aren't just bandits. This is the stage of building a local reputation.


Tier 3: The Renowned (5-10 AP)
Title: Heroes of the Hold, "The Investigators of Whiterun."
In-World Effect: Their fame has spread to a few neighboring holds. Jarls and important guild masters now seek them out by name for difficult or sensitive tasks. They are recognized as regional players.
Mechanical Benefit: They may gain Advantage on one social roll per adventure when dealing with someone who has heard of their heroic deeds.


Tier 4: The Legendary (11-18 AP)
Title: The Saviors of Falkreath, The Wardens of Skyrim.
In-World Effect: Their deeds are becoming the stuff of songs and legends. Bards sing tales of their exploits in taverns across the province. Common folk recognize them on sight. Their reputation alone can intimidate lesser foes or open doors to the highest levels of power.
Mechanical Benefit: Their reputation is now a tangible force. Once per adventure, they can declare their identity to automatically succeed on one Intimidation check against common foes or one Persuasion check with a common citizen.


Tier 5: The Mythic (19+ AP)
Title: Their names are spoken alongside figures from history. They are living myths.
In-World Effect: Their actions are now shaping the future of Skyrim. The fate of the province may hinge on their decisions. Jarls defer to their counsel, and entire holds might rally to their cause. Their presence can inspire hope or fear in entire populations. They are no longer just heroes; they are historical figures in the making.
Mechanical Benefit: The party's legend is so great it inspires others to greatness (or folly). Once per adventure, they can call upon their mythic status to rally a group of NPCs, turning a neutral crowd friendly or a friendly crowd into zealous allies for a single scene.

Addendum: Player-Driven Campaign Progression
To ensure player agency is at the heart of the campaign, the path from one adventure to the next will not be predetermined by the GM. Instead, at the conclusion of each self-contained adventure, the party will be presented with a choice of where to go and what to tackle next. This is handled through the Rumor Mill mechanic.
The Rumor Mill: The Choice Point
After the party has concluded an adventure, collected their rewards, and is preparing to leave their current location with Bjorn, he will serve as their primary source of information. Drawing on his experience as a traveling merchant and the whispers he's heard at inns and stables, Bjorn will present the party with three potential leads—rumors of trouble or opportunity in different parts of Skyrim.
The players, as a group, must then decide which lead to follow. This choice determines their next destination and the next adventure module we will play.
The Three Paths
Each set of rumors will be crafted to offer three distinct types of adventures, giving the players a meaningful choice that will shape the direction of the campaign. The three paths are:
1. The Path of Prophecy (The Main Quest)
Nature of the Lead: This rumor will always be the one most directly connected to the escalating Dragon Cult crisis and the main story arc. It will be subtle at first—strange weather patterns, entire villages going silent, sightings of robed figures near ancient Nordic ruins—but will grow more overt and dire as the campaign progresses.
GM's Role: This is the thread that advances the overarching plot. Following this path will lead the party to encounters with Dragon Priests, clues about Alduin, and eventually, the quest for the Elder Scroll.
Example Rumors:
(Early Campaign): "Strange thing... I heard from a traveler from Kynesgrove that the whole town's been spooked. Said a robed man was seen chanting at the dragon burial mound outside town, and now the air itself feels wrong."
(Mid Campaign): "The Jarl of Dawnstar has put out a call for sellswords. A whole Imperial patrol vanished near High Gate Ruins. No bodies, no survivors, just... gone. The locals are terrified, sayin' the dead are walking the mountain passes at night."


2. The Path of Steel (The Civil War)
Nature of the Lead: This rumor is directly tied to the ongoing Civil War. It will present an opportunity to aid either the Imperial Legion or the Stormcloak rebellion in a key strategic mission.
GM's Role: Following this path allows the party to influence the balance of power in Skyrim. Their actions will determine which faction gains control of holds, forts, and resources. This path directly interacts with the Civil War Counter-Clock.
Example Rumors:
(Imperial): "Legate Rikke is mustering forces in the Pale. I heard she's paying top coin for a specialist team to infiltrate Fort Dunstad and 'acquire' the Stormcloak battle plans before their next offensive."
(Stormcloak): "Galmar Stone-Fist is furious. An Imperial patrol captured one of his key messengers near Whiterun. He's offering a bounty—no questions asked—to anyone who can intercept the patrol and retrieve the courier's satchel before it reaches General Tullius."


3. The Path of Fortune (The Personal Quest)
Nature of the Lead: This rumor is not about a grand, world-saving event, but about something personal, immediate, and often lucrative. This path serves two crucial functions: it offers classic, self-contained "monster of the week" adventures, and more importantly, it is the primary avenue for players to pursue personal character arcs.
GM's Role: This is the most flexible and player-centric path. The leads for this path will be drawn directly from:
Player Backstories: A character's estranged sibling is in trouble, a rival from their past has been spotted nearby, or a clue to their family's lost treasure has surfaced.
"Order of Business" Consequences: An NPC the party helped (or wronged) in a previous city now needs their aid, or a deal they made has a new complication.
Classic Adventure Hooks: Monster hunts, local mysteries, Daedric shrine quests, or rumors of a treasure-filled ruin.


Example Rumors:
(Personal Backstory - Warrior): "Bjorn, that contact you paid to keep an ear out for news of your old mercenary company sent a message. He says your former captain, the one who betrayed you, was just seen heading into a Draugr-infested ruin in the Pale. The locals say he was looking for some ancient axe."
(Order of Business - Rogue): "That Thieves Guild contact you made in Riften needs a favor. She says a job has gone sideways, and she needs a 'neutral third party' to retrieve a sensitive ledger from a heavily guarded manor in Solitude before her client gets impatient."
(Standalone Adventure): "The Jarl of Morthal is offering a bounty on a powerful vampire that's been terrorizing the swamps. It's dangerous work, but the pay is good, and they say the Jarl will look kindly on anyone who solves his 'undead problem.'"


Consequences of Choice
The world does not wait. When the party chooses one path, the other two do not simply disappear. They evolve according to the Consequence Calendar.
If the party ignores the Path of Prophecy, the Dragon Cult's plans will advance unimpeded, and the world will become a darker, more dangerous place.
If the party ignores the Path of Steel, the Civil War will stagnate or shift in ways beyond their control, potentially leading to a faction they dislike gaining the upper hand.
If the party ignores the Path of Fortune, that specific opportunity may be lost. The monster might be slain by other adventurers, the treasure might be found, or the person in need might succumb to their fate.
This mechanic ensures that every choice is meaningful, every adventure is player-driven, and the world feels alive and constantly changing around them.


